      <h3>Introduction of Wireless Communication</h3>
      <p>The wired network technology has come a long way from its inception in the 1800s. It continues to develop and push the boundaries of speed as researchers find faster ways to transport data, much like wireless network communications.</p>
    </div>
<div class="images">
 <img src="C:\Users\yuvra\OneDrive\Desktop\2.jfif">
 </div>
    
    <div class="event">
      <h3>Wireless Networking</h3>
      <p>The drawbacks of wired networks became obvious as computer networks spread throughout society. Device mobility was restricted by cables, making it challenging to expand the network or add new devices without extensive rewiring. To overcome these restrictions, wireless networks were created, and they quickly gained acceptance.</p>
    </div>
<div>
	<p>To transfer data between devices, wireless networks use radio waves. In the 1980s, private technology were employed to create the first wireless networks. In comp
These early networks were slower than wired networks and frequently had a smaller coverage area. Wireless networks, however, grew quicker and more dependable as technology advanced.</p>
</div>
<div class="images">
 <img src="C:\Users\yuvra\OneDrive\Desktop\3.jfif">
 </div>
    
    <div class="event">
      <h3>Evolution of Communication</h3>
      <p>Broadband networks and communication have advanced for more than a century. The following are some of the most influential developments in wired network technology throughout history that have inspired current developments:</p>
    </div>
    
  <div>
      <p>1876: The invention of the telephone started a revolution towards wired communications.</p>
<p>1964: With the introduction of optical fiber, the potential of wired networks skyrocketed.</p>
<p>1970: Ethernet technology, which uses a coaxial-based or twisted copper transport system was developed.</p>
<p>1980: During this decade, researchers built the foundation for a digital subscriber line (DSL).</p>
<p>2000: Broadband technology became available to consumers. Today, more than 20 million users trust it.</p>
<p>As was seen, the history of wired network technology has focused on finding new methods for data delivery.</p>
    </div>
<div class="images">
 <img src="C:\Users\yuvra\OneDrive\Desktop\4.jfif">
 </div>
 <div class="event">
<h3>Wi-FI</h3>
<div>
      <p>Wireless networks are widely used today and may be found in everything from smart homes to mobile phones. The most widely used wireless networking technology is Wi-Fi, which is utilised in homes, offices, and public places all over the world. Wi-Fi has transformed the way we work, communicate, and access information by enabling devices to connect to the internet without the use of actual cords.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="images">
 <img src="C:\Users\yuvra\OneDrive\Desktop\5.jfif">
 </div>
 <div class="event">
<h3>BlueTooth</h3>
    <div>
      <p>There are numerous other wireless networking protocols in use today in addition to Wi-Fi. Cellular networks are necessary for mobile phones and other mobile devices because they allow mobile devices to connect to the internet utilising cellular data networks. Another widely used wireless technology is Bluetooth, which is used for close-quarters communication, like linking a speaker and a phone.</p>
    </div>
